          "body": "The chapter's most precise and most damning number is not forty years but twenty-three. In the twenty-third year of Jehoash, the priests had still not repaired the temple (12:6). This was not an unknown failure — the king himself had issued a clear decree in the early years of his reign (12:4-5), directing all sacred revenue to temple repair, assigning each priest responsibility for his own acquaintances. The system existed; the authorization existed; the money was flowing in. What did not happen was the work. The historian gives no explanation for the failure — no competing demands, no shortage of material, no theological objection. The silence is eloquent: institutional structures, left without accountability, tend toward self-preservation rather than service. The priests were receiving funds from their acquaintances (12:5) and apparently keeping them rather than deploying them for repair. When Jehoash finally confronts Jehoiada and the priests (12:7), the response is not repentance but withdrawal: they agree to take no more money from the people and to do no more repairs (12:8). They abdicate rather than reform. The institutional lesson is one that every generation of religious leadership must reckon with: the gap between institutional mandate and institutional performance can widen for decades while leaders collect their income and the building crumbles."
