        "excerpt": "Jehoash did right in the sight of the LORD all his days in which Jehoiada the priest instructed him.",
        "body": "The opening evaluation of Jehoash is the chapter's hermeneutical key. The Deuteronomistic historian uses a standard evaluative formula throughout Kings — 'he did right/evil in the sight of the LORD' — but Jehoash receives a version of the positive formula that is immediately subdivided by a temporal clause: 'all his days in which Jehoiada the priest instructed him.' No other king in the book of Kings receives this exact qualification. The positive verdict is real but bounded.\n\nThe significance of Jehoiada cannot be overstated. It was Jehoiada who hid the infant Jehoash in the temple for six years while Athaliah's usurpation ran its course (2 Kings 11:1-4). It was Jehoiada who organized the coup that restored the Davidic line (11:4-16) and oversaw the covenant renewal between the LORD, the king, and the people (11:17). Jehoash owed his life, his throne, and his theological formation to this man. The dependence was not unhealthy in itself — Proverbs 13:20 commends the wisdom of walking with the wise. But the Deuteronomistic narrative, read alongside 2 Chronicles 24, reveals that the dependence was never transcended: Jehoash never became a man of covenant conviction in his own right.\n\nThe high places of verse 3 confirm this. Every reforming king in Judah who receives a positive evaluation faces the same caveat: 'only the high places were not taken away' (cf. 1 Kings 15:14; 22:43; 2 Kings 14:4; 15:4, 35). The high places were local worship sites where sacrifice and incense-burning continued outside the Levitical system, in violation of Deuteronomy 12:1-14. Their persistence in Jehoash's reign signals that the reform was institutional — centered on the temple building — rather than popular, reaching the hearts and worship habits of the common people. A leader whose piety is derivative tends to produce reforms that are structural rather than transformative.\n\nThe pastoral implication for the Deuteronomist's audience — exiles in Babylon reading their national history — is pointed: a generation raised on borrowed faith is a generation that cannot sustain covenant loyalty when the borrowed support is withdrawn. The call of Deuteronomy 6:4-9 was for covenant love inscribed on the heart, taught to children, spoken at home and on the road. Jehoash received instruction (yara, 12:2 — the same root as Torah) but never internalized it as his own.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yara* (instructed, v.2) shares the root with *Torah* — the instruction Jehoash received was priestly and covenantal. *Bamah* (high places, v.3) — plural, scattered sites. *Raq* (only, v.3) is the historian's standard caveat-marker, signaling partial rather than complete reform."
